It is usually presumed that Alice and Bob hold sifted keys x and y, two n-bit strings that are outcomes of X and Y. During reconciliation, Alice and Bob communicate a set of messages M to reconcile their keys. At the end of the protocol, they agree on a shared secret key in the presence of Eve while revealing some information. Therefore, X and Y can be considered correlated random variables, and y is given by transition probability í µí±ƒí µí±ƒí µí±ƒí µí µí±ƒí±Ší µí±Ší µí±Ší µí±Š{í µí°±í µí°±í µí°±í µí°±|í µí°²í µí°²í µí°²í µí°²} . It is given as if every symbol was generated by memoryless channel W, equivalently. Errors occurred during QKD are commonly considered as uncorrelated and symmetric. Thus, the memoryless channel W can be seen as a binary symmetric channel (BSC). The crossover probability p of the BSC is generally supposed as given.

The problem is how a message M is encoded. This problem of reconciliation can be treated as well-known Slepian-Wolf coding, which is a way of encoding two lossless compressed correlated sources [9]. The Slepian-Wolf bound states that (í µí±‹í µí±‹í µí±‹í µí±‹í µí±›í µí±›í µí±›í µí±›, í µí±Œí µí±Œí µí±Œí µí±Œí µí±›í µí±›í µí±›í µí±›) can be compressed into more than í µí±›í µí±›í µí±›í µí±›í µí±›í µí±›í µí±›í µí±›(í µí±‹í µí±‹í µí±‹í µí±‹|í µí±Œí µí±Œí µí±Œí µí±Œ) bits without information loss. This is the minimum information required to agree on a secret key. In practice, codewords will be encoded with a rate í µí±“í µí±“í µí±“í µí±“í µí±›í µí±›í µí±›í µí±›(í µí±‹í µí±‹í µí±‹í µí±‹|í µí±Œí µí±Œí µí±Œí µí±Œ) , where í µí±“í µí±“í µí±“í µí±“ is the reconciliation efficiency. Therefore, efficiency is defined as

