Lower efficiency means fewer information leaks during reconciliation. More information remains in sifted keys, leading to a higher secret key rate. After all, a lower efficiency is directly related to the higher secret key rate, which is why efficiency is a performance indicator of reconciliation protocols.

III. PRELIMINARIES

A. Polar Codes
The development of polar codes by Arikan [10] was a major advance in coding theory. Polar codes have been proven to

achieve the capacity of symmetric binary-input discrete memoryless channels (BI-DMC) with an explicit construction. Moreover, polar codes have low encoding and decoding complexity, which makes them suitable for efficient hardware implementation [11].

With the Arikanâ€™s construction method [10], the generation matrix of a polar code is an í µí±›í µí±›í µí±›í µí±› Ã— í µí±›í µí±›í µí±›í µí±› matrix í µí°ºí µí°ºí µí°ºí µí°º = í µí°µí µí°µí µí°µí µí µí°µí±›í µí±›í µí±›í µí±›í µí°¹í µí°¹í µí°¹í µí°¹âŠ—í µí±ší µí±ší µí±ší µí±š, where í µí±›í µí±›í µí±›í µí±› = 2í µí±ší µí±ší µí±ší µí±š, í µí°µí µí°µí µí°µí µí°µí µí±í µí±í µí±í µí± is the bit reversal permutation matrix [10], and í µí°¹í µí°¹í µí°¹í µí°¹ = ï¿½11 01ï¿½ . Here âŠ— í µí±ší µí±ší µí±ší µí±š denotes the í µí±ší µí±ší µí±ší µí±š th Kronecker power and í µí°¹í µí°¹í µí°¹í µí°¹âŠ—í µí±ší µí±ší µí±ší µí±š = F âŠ— í µí°¹í µí°¹í µí°¹í µí°¹(í µí±ší µí±ší µí±ší µí±ší µí±ší µí±š) . Let í µí±¢í µí±¢í µí±¢í µí±¢0í µí±›í µí±›í µí±›í µí±› = (í µí±¢í µí±¢í µí±¢í µí±¢0, í µí±¢í µí±¢í µí±¢í µí±¢1, â‹¯ , í µí±¢í µí±¢í µí±¢í µí±¢í µí±›í µí±›í µí±›í µí±›) denote uncoded data bits and í µí±¥í µí±¥í µí±¥í µí±¥0í µí±›í µí±›í µí±›í µí±› = (í µí±¥í µí±¥í µí±¥í µí±¥0, í µí±¥í µí±¥í µí±¥í µí±¥1, â‹¯ , í µí±¥í µí±¥í µí±¥í µí±¥í µí±›í µí±›í µí±›í µí±›) encoded bits, then í µí±¥í µí±¥í µí±¥í µí±¥í µí±œí µí µí±›í±œí µí µí±›í±œí µí µí±›í±œí µí±› = í µí±¢í µí±¢í µí±¢í µí±¢í µí µí±œí±›í µí µí±œí±›í µí µí±œí±›í µí±œí µí±›í µí°ºí µí°ºí µí°ºí µí°º. An (í µí±í µí±í µí±í µí±, í µí°¾í µí°¾í µí°¾í µí°¾) polar code is defined by setting í µí±í µí±í µí±í µí± í µí±  bits of í µí±¢í µí±¢í µí±¢í µí±¢0í µí±›í µí±›í µí±›í µí±› to zero, denoted as frozen bits. The information is transmitted by the rest í µí°¾í µí°¾í µí°¾í µí°¾ bits, denoted as
information bits.

B. Soft Cancellation Decoding
The belief propagation (BP) decoding of polar codes over factor graph was proposed in [10]. Compared with their SC counterparts, polar BP decoders are easier to achieve lowlatency. However, polar BP decoder need a large number of iterations and suffer from high computation complexity. On this account, a soft cancellation (SCAN) decoder is proposed in [17]. The SCAN decoding algorithm makes use of a serial message updating schedule, which is similar to the SC decoder of polar codes. By limiting the soft information propagation schedule in the decoding process, the computational complexity of SCAN decoders is much lower than that of polar BP decoders.

The SCAN decoding is conducted over the factor graph, which is derived from the encoding equations. The corresponding factor graph of a polar code with í µí±›í µí±›í µí±›í µí±› = 8 is shown in Fig. 1. This factor graph shows relationship between uncoded and encoded bits. In graph, Î» denotes layers and í µí¼™í µí¼™í µí¼™í µí¼™ denotes groups. Basic element of factor graph is represented in Fig. 2. Here í µí¼”í µí¼”í µí¼”í µí¼” denotes the node number in group. Each node has two associated LLR messages í µí°¿í µí°¿í µí°¿í µí°¿í µí¼†í µí¼†í µí¼†í µí¼†(í µí¼™í µí¼™í µí¼™í µí¼™, í µí¼”í µí¼”í µí¼”í µí¼”) and í µí°µí µí°µí µí°µí µí µí°µí¼†í µí¼†í µí¼†í µí¼†(í µí¼™í µí¼™í µí¼™í µí¼™, í µí¼”í µí¼”í µí¼”í µí¼”) which are passed to the right and left directions of factor graph. These messages can be computed as follows

